Lecture 2 -- Digital software for simulating quantum dynamics¶

Edwin Ng (16 July 2021)

Introduction¶

What are some useful features provided by software packages for quantum simulation?

  • Numerical representations of quantum states (e.g., as vectors)
  • Numerical representations of quantum operators (e.g., as matrices/tensors)
  • Convenience constructors for common states/operators -- Fock states, projectors, ladder operators, etc.
  • Convenience functions for quantum-specific algebra -- expectations, tensor products, partial traces, etc.
  • Routines for computing special states like eigenstates, dynamical steady states, etc.
  • Routines for calculating dynamics (e.g., Schrodinger equation, Monte Carlo wavefunction)
  • Methods for visualizing quantum states and properties (e.g., phase space distributions, histograms, correlation spectra)

When are quantum simulations useful?¶

Quantum states and quantum dynamics are intrinsically multi- (and often high-) dimensional. Numerical experiments can be helpful if used right.

  • Getting intuition about how small-scale quantum systems behave
  • Especially useful when detailed information about dynamics are desired
  • Designing quantum experiments and predicting/analyzing/validating experimental results/data

Limitations¶

  • In general, quantum systems cannot be efficiently simulated ("quantum advantage"?)
  • Semiclassical systems can also be hard to simulate using software meant for quantum systems
  • Workflow and abstractions are still rather low-level: quantum systems are specified from bottom up on the device level
  • Systematic numerical methodology is important to ensure physical results (always run checks for convergence!)

Software ecosystem¶

There are many software packages out there for simulating quantum physics -- https://quantiki.org/wiki/list-qc-simulators. Fair to say they are all specialized for some class of systems/states someone cares about.

For the subfield of quantum optics, the most generally useful packages provide capabilities for interacting photonic modes and/or atoms, with an emphasis on open quantum system dynamics.

We focus on the "Quantum Optics Toolbox" family:

  • qotoolbox (MATLAB): https://qo.phy.auckland.ac.nz/toolbox/
  • QuTiP (Python): https://qutip.org/
  • QuantumOptics.jl (Julia): https://qojulia.org/

Code below will be for QuTiP (results are usually portable among QO toolboxes).

Part 1: Visualizing quantum states¶

Let's take a look at some quantum states. States are just vectors in Hilbert space, so the most natural representation of a quantum state is a vector of complex numbers. QuTiP provides convenience functions for constructing common states and visualization options for thinking about them.

Spin 1/2 (qubit) states¶

The simplest quantum state is a 2-level system, equivalent to a qubit or a spin-1/2 atom. It has the general form

$$ |\psi\rangle = \cos(\theta/2) |0\rangle + e^{\mathrm{i}\phi}\sin(\theta/2) |1\rangle, $$

where $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ are the "spin-up" and "spin-down" states. They are one possible basis, consisting of the eigenstates of the Pauli-Z operator $\hat\sigma_z$ with eigenvalues $+1$ and $-1$ respectively.

The coordinates $(\theta,\phi)$ nicely parameterize a spherical coordinate system with unit radius. There is however, an "odd" factor of two in the polar angle, making "up" and "down" orthogonal.

States of the harmonic oscillator¶

Another quantized degree of freedom central to quantum optics is the quantum harmonic oscillator, or more specifically a quantized harmonic oscillator mode. States of the harmonic oscillator mode have the general form

$$ |\phi\rangle = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} c_n |n\rangle, $$

where $|n\rangle$ is an eigenstate of the number operator $\hat n = \hat a^\dagger \hat a$, for mode annihilation and creation operators satisfying $[\hat a, \hat a^\dagger] = 1$.

For numerical simulations, the infinite sum cannot be represented, so we instead choose a cutoff $N_\text{fock}$. This requires that we deal with states that have bounded excitation ($c_n \approx 0$ for $n > N_\text{fock}$). This also means that, numerically, there isn't that much difference between a $d$-level atom and a harmonic oscillator mode truncated to $N_\text{fock} = d$.

For a mode to exist, there must be some physical Hamiltonian $\hbar\omega(\hat a^\dagger \hat a + 1/2)$ that defines it and its natural oscillation frequency. However, we often work in a rotating frame in which this term (which produces trivial dynamics) can be ignored. Instead, our "Hamiltonians" will be numerically specified as perturbations of the physical Hamiltonian. Some examples are:

  • Detuning: $\Delta\hat a^\dagger \hat a$ ($\Delta \ll \omega$)
  • Linear mode coupling: $\theta(\hat a^\dagger \hat b + \hat a \hat b^\dagger)$
  • Coherent driving: $\alpha \hat a^\dagger + \alpha^* \hat a$
  • Squeezing: $\eta(a^2 + a^{\dagger2})$
  • Kerr nonlinearity: $\chi \hat a^{\dagger2} \hat a^2$
  • Many more...

Numerically, we represent the state in the Fock basis, but another representation is given by the canonical position and momentum operators

$$ \hat q = \frac{\hat a + \hat a^\dagger}{\sqrt{2}} \qquad\quad \hat p = \frac{\hat a - \hat a^\dagger}{\sqrt{2}\mathrm{i}}. $$

If $\phi(q) = \sum_n c_n \langle q | n \rangle$, then $$ |\phi\rangle = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \mathrm{d}q \, \phi(q) \, |q\rangle. $$

Here, $|q\rangle$ are the eigenstates of $\hat q$ (delta functions), $\phi(q)$ is the (position-basis) wavefunction of the state, and $\langle q|n \rangle$ are the (position-basis) wavefunctions of the eigenstates of the quantum harmonic oscillators (Hermite-Gauss functions). If you've studied the second quantization of the (single-particle, nonrelativistic) harmonic oscillator, this is just going backwards through the derivation.

Intuitively:

  • A mode oscillates with some amplitude, and states of quantized amplitude correspond to the Fock basis
  • The cosine and sine components of the oscillation correspond to the canonical position and momentum
  • For modes where "position" and "momentum" do not have the usual particle meaning (e.g., electromagnetic modes), they're often called the position and momentum quadratures or sometimes in-phase and quadrature components

Because quadratures are so useful for understanding the state of an oscillator mode, we often represent the state in terms of its quadratures. There are many such phase-space representations (e.g., Glauber-Sudarshan P, Husimi Q, Wigner, etc.), but we will go with the Wigner representation in our visualizations.

The formal description of the Wigner function is a bit complicated (see References for excellent introductions). However, very roughly:

  • For each quantum state $|\phi\rangle$ of a single mode there is a corresponding Wigner function $W_\phi(q,p): \mathbb R^2 \mapsto \mathbb R$.
  • It is a quasi-probability distribution: $\int W_\phi(q,p) \, \mathrm{d}p = |\langle q | \phi \rangle|^2$ (and vice-versa for $q$), but $W(q,p)$ can be negative (a sign of non-classicality)!
  • Thus it gives a sense for how measurements of $\hat q$ and $\hat p$ might be distributed, and how they might also be correlated.

Part 2: Closed and open quantum dynamics¶

For closed systems, time evolution is governed by the Schrodinger equation. We simply need to specify a Hamiltonian $\hat H$ made up of system operators and the state is given by $\mathrm{i}\partial_t |\psi\rangle = \hat H |\psi\rangle$, or if we let $\hat\rho$ be a density matrix, then more generally, $\mathrm{i}\partial_t \hat\rho = \big[\hat H, \hat\rho\big]$.

For open systems, the entire environment in principle needs to take part in the dynamics, which would be intractable due to the essentially infinite number of degrees of freedom it introduces.

Quantum input-output theory is a way of treating the reservoir without incurring this cost. It works when the system only weakly excites the reservoir, because the coupling is weak and the reservoir is large.

Image credit: R. Hamerly, PhD Thesis, Stanford University, 2018, Fig. 1.1

Very roughly, the physical arguments go as follows:

  1. Start with a full Schrodinger equation for the evolution of the system and reservoir
  2. Attempt to partial-trace out the reservoir
  3. Make a Born approximation: When calculating the perturbative contribution of the total system+reservoir state to the reduced system state's differential evolution, assume that the system and reservoir can be factorized, and the reservoir part of the state is time-independent.
  4. Make a Markov approximation: Even after everything above, the resulting equation of motion still has memory: it depends on an integral of the system's state history. If the reservoir is very large, we can assume its memory kernel is sharply peaked (e.g., a delta function in correlation time), which turns the integral into a constant coupling rate.

The resulting master equation in Lindblad form is

$$ \partial_t \hat\rho = -\mathrm{i}\left[\hat H, \hat\rho\right] + \sum_i \left(\hat L_i\hat\rho\hat L_i^\dagger - \frac 1 2 \left\{\hat L_i^\dagger\hat L_i, \hat\rho\right\}\right). $$
  • The operators $\hat L_i$ are Lindblad operators that characterize the effect of each reservoir the system is coupled with. Can be viewed as "dissipation channels" through which state information can leak out.
  • This is a linear equation of motion (just like the Schrodinger equation) in $\hat\rho$. The linear superoperator acting on $\hat\rho$ is the Liouvillian or sometimes the Lindbladian.

Closed system dynamics¶

We start with the foundational model of light-matter interaction in quantum optics: the Jaynes-Cummings model. This system involves one qubit and one oscillator mode which exchange excitations with a coupling rate $g$:

$$ \hat H_\text{JC} = g\left(\hat\sigma^\dagger\hat a + \hat\sigma\hat a^\dagger\right). $$

This model can be very rich, but we focus on just the basics here, so we ignore detuning and drive.

In [27]:
Nfock_jc = 5
σ = qt.tensor(qt.sigmam(),qt.qeye(Nfock_jc))
a_jc = qt.tensor(qt.qeye(2),qt.destroy(Nfock_jc))
In [28]:
g = 1
H_jc = g*(σ.dag()*a_jc + σ*a_jc.dag())
In [29]:

Part 3: Quantum measurement¶

Information leaked out of the system into the reservoir is not necessarily lost completely!

  • We can't track the reservoir's full quantum state but can convert its entanglement with the system into classical information via measurement.
  • Quantum measurements have intrinsic uncertainty, so the results are stochastic -- we obtain a "measurement record".
  • After the measurement, the system state partially collapses into the part of the wavefunction consistent with the measurement result -- the system undergoes a "quantum jump" or experiences "backaction" due to the measurement.
  • The conditional dynamics of the system thus depend on the measurement model used.
  • Averaging any physical quantity over multiple measurement records (i.e., throwing away measurement information) results in the same result as calculating that quantity using the Lindblad master equation.
  • The conditional dynamics are an "unravelling" of the master equation.

Image credit: (Left) Y. Yamamoto, PHI Lab Lecture #1 (2021) , Fig. 2.5; (Right) R. Hamerly, PhD Thesis, Stanford University (2018), Fig. 1.2

Within input-output theory:

  • The interactions with the reservoir take place continuously in every differential time step
  • Each interaction is infinitesimally weak, but there are infinitely many interactions
  • The reservoir before the interaction is uncorrelated with the system and in a known (e.g., vacuum) state
  • After the interaction, the reservoir is weakly entangled with the system, but we immediately measure its state according to a specified measurement model

Some useful measurement models include:

  • Photon counting: Basis for the Monte Carlo wavefunction (MCWF) method. In each time step, we either get no click (evolve deterministically according to a non-Hermitian Hamiltonian) or we get a single click (perform a quantum jump to remove a photon from the system (for the case where the Lindblad operator is $\propto \hat a$).
  • Homodyne: Same idea as photon counting, but now bias the output with a strong classical local oscillator. Then, there will be a jump of some kind every time step, but they are "infinitely small jumps (which) occur infinitely frequently" [6]. Notably gives continuous monitoring of a quadrature, chosen by the local oscillator.
  • Heterodyne: Similar to homodyne, but for both quadratures at once (producing a complex number as measurement result).

Image credit: R. Hamerly, PhD Thesis, Stanford University (2018), Fig. 1.4

Degenerate OPO near threshold¶

Our last model will be a single-mode system for which dissipation plays a big role in much of its qualitative behavior: the degenerate optical parametric oscillator (DOPO). The model consists of a squeezing Hamiltonian

$$ \hat H_\text{dopo} = \frac{\mathrm{i}r}{2} \left(a^{\dagger2} - a^2\right) $$

and two Lindblad operators $\hat L_\text{lin} = \sqrt{2\kappa} \hat a$ and $\hat L_\text{nl} = \sqrt{\eta} \hat a^2$. The latter Lindblad operator is actually nonlinear and is responsible for thresholding behavior in the DOPO, since for $r > \kappa$, the linear part of the dynamics is actually unstable; the nonlinearity is thus a dissipative term that stablizes the system.

In [78]:
Nfock = 50
r = 0.95
η = 0.05
κ = 1

a = qt.destroy(Nfock)
H = 1j*r/2 * (a.dag()**2 - a**2)
L_lin = sqrt(2*κ)*a
L_nl = sqrt(η)*a**2

q = (a+a.dag())/sqrt(2)
p = (a-a.dag())/(1j*sqrt(2))
n = a.dag()*a

ψ0 = qt.basis(Nfock, 0)
t = np.linspace(0, 20, 501)
In [79]:
sol_me = qt.mesolve(H, ψ0, t, [L_lin,L_nl])
sol_trajs = [
    qt.mcsolve(H, ψ0, t, [L_lin,L_nl], ntraj=1),
    qt.ssesolve(H, ψ0, t, [L_lin,L_nl], nsubsteps=100, ntraj=1),
    qt.ssesolve(H, ψ0, t, [1j*L_lin,L_nl], nsubsteps=100, ntraj=1)
]

def animate(j):
    for i in range(3):
        W_plots[i].set_array(wigner_trajs[i][j])
        q_plot.set_data(t[:j], expt_trajs[1][:j])
        p_plot.set_data(t[:j], expt_trajs[2][:j])
        n_plot.set_data(t[:j], expt_trajs[0][:j])
    return (*W_plots, q_plot, p_plot, n_plot)

anim = ani.FuncAnimation(fig, animate, frames=len(t), interval=20, blit=True, repeat_delay=2000)
